evolution leaps forward.

5
00:04:24,931 --> 00:04:28,531
Niagara Falls, up the Canadian Rockies,

6
00:04:29,169 --> 00:04:32,628
and then it's only
a few hundred miles to Anchorage.

7
00:04:33,240 --> 00:04:36,610
- Won't it be cold?
- That's the point, stupid.

8
00:04:37,210 --> 00:04:39,870
Otherwise it wouldn't be an adventure.

9
00:04:40,380 --> 00:04:42,810
And when are you gonna do this?

10
00:04:45,218 --> 00:04:47,648
I don't know.

11
00:04:48,155 --> 00:04:51,085
After high school. Before college.

12
00:05:35,635 --> 00:05:37,625
- Marie!
- [ don't know what happened.

13
00:05:38,038 --> 00:05:41,468
- David?
- I don't know... l just touched him.

14
00:05:42,075 --> 00:05:44,655
- [didn’t mean...
- Call an ambulance!

15
00:05:45,178 --> 00:05:47,698
We only touched. Just get away from me!

16
00:05:48,215 --> 00:05:51,174
- Will you call an ambulance?
- Don't touch me!

17
00:05:52,686 --> 00:05:57,876
We are now seeing the beginnings
of another stage of human evolution.

18
00:05:58,725 --> 00:06:03,585
These mutations manifest at puberty, often
triggered by periods of emotional stress.

19
00:06:04,431 --> 00:06:07,270
Thank you, Miss Grey.
It was quite educational.

20
00:06:07,868 --> 00:06:11,647
However, it fails to address the issue
that is the focus of this hearing.

21
00:06:12,305 --> 00:06:15,585
Three words: are mutants dangerous?

22
00:06:16,209 --> 00:06:21,249
That's unfair, Senator Kelly. The wrong
person driving a car can be dangerous.

23
00:06:22,082 --> 00:06:25,332
- We do license people to drive.
- Yes, but not to live.

24
00:06:26,486 --> 00:06:30,966
Senator, mutants who've come forward
and revealed themselves publicly

25
00:06:31,725 --> 00:06:34,855
have been met with fear,
hostility, even violence.

26
00:06:35,462 --> 00:06:37,602
It is because of that hostility

27
00:06:38,064 --> 00:06:41,724
that I am urging the Senate
to vote against mutant registration.

28
00:06:42,369 --> 00:06:45,299
- To force mutants to expose themselves...
- Expose themselves?

29
00:06:45,906 --> 00:06:50,006
What do mutants have to hide that makes
them so afraid to identify themselves?

30
00:06:50,710 --> 00:06:54,400
- I didn't say they were hiding.
- Let me show you what is being hidden.

31
00:06:55,081 --> 00:07:00,121
I have here a list of names of identified
mutants living right here in the United States.

32
00:07:00,954 --> 00:07:04,234
- Senator Kelly...
- Agirl in Illinois who walks through walls.

33
00:07:04,891 --> 00:07:08,871
What's to stop her from walking
into a bank vault? Or into the White House?

34
00:07:09,562 --> 00:07:14,312
Or into their houses? And there are even
rumors of mutants so powerful

35
00:07:15,101 --> 00:07:17,851
that they can enter our minds
and control our thoughts,

36
00:07:18,371 --> 00:07:20,541
taking away our God-given free will.

37
00:07:20,974 --> 00:07:25,074
The American people deserve the right
to decide whether they want their children

38
00:07:25,779 --> 00:07:29,259
to be in school with mutants.
To be taught by mutants.

39
00:07:31,584 --> 00:07:36,274
Ladies and gentlemen,
the truth is that mutants are very real.

40
00:07:38,191 --> 00:07:42,111
And they are among us.
We must know who they are,

41
00:07:42,796 --> 00:07:46,396
and, above all,
we must know what they can do.

42
00:08:10,657 --> 00:08:12,436
Eric.

43
00:08:15,128 --> 00:08:16,878
What are you doing here?

44
00:08:17,263 --> 00:08:20,983
Why do you ask questions to which
you already know the answers?

45
00:08:21,634 --> 00:08:25,444
- Don't give up on them, Eric.
- What would you have me do, Charles?

46
00:08:26,139 --> 00:08:29,099
I've heard these arguments before.

47
00:08:29,642 --> 00:08:33,302
It was a long time ago.
Mankind has evolved since then.

48
00:08:34,347 --> 00:08:37,156
Yes... Into us.

49
00:08:43,789 --> 00:08:48,860
Are you sneaking around in here, Charles?
Whatever are you looking for?

50
00:08:55,869 --> 00:08:57,709
I'm looking for hope.

51
00:08:59,272 --> 00:09:04,632
I will bring you hope, old friend.
And [ask only one thing in return.

52
00:09:07,414 --> 00:09:09,524
Don't get in my way.

53
00:09:13,586 --> 00:09:17,276
We are the future, Charles, not them.
They no longer matter.

54
00:09:31,938 --> 00:09:33,747
This is it.

55
00:09:41,815 --> 00:09:45,795
Where are we? I thought you said you were
gonna take me as far as Laughlin City.

56
00:09:46,486 --> 00:09:48,236
This is Laughlin City.

57
00:10:20,120 --> 00:10:24,280
Gentlemen, in all my years
I've never seen anything like this.

58
00:10:26,559 --> 00:10:30,459
Are you gonna let this man
walk away with your money?

59
00:10:31,131 --> 00:10:32,271
No!

60
00:10:32,565 --> 00:10:35,055
lll fight him!

61
00:10:37,170 --> 00:10:39,479
Ladies and gentlemen,

62
00:10:39,939 --> 00:10:41,748
-
our savior.

63
00:10:43,476 --> 00:10:45,346
Don't hit him in the balls.

64
00:10:45,745 --> 00:10:49,665
- You said anything goes.
- Anything goes, but he'll take it personal.

65
00:11:02,295 --> 00:11:03,665
You idiot!

66
00:11:16,609 --> 00:11:21,849
Ladies and gentlemen,
tonight's winner and still King of the Cage,

67
00:11:22,749 --> 00:11:24,829
the Wolverine.

68
00:11:53,980 --> 00:11:58,340
You want something new, honey?
Or are you sticking with water?

69
00:12:07,994 --> 00:12:09,744
I'll have a beer.

70
00:12:19,606 --> 00:12:23,266
Ellis island, once the arrival point
for American immigrants,

71
00:12:23,910 --> 00:12:25,750
is opening its doors again.

72
00:12:26,212 --> 00:12:29,752
Preparations are nearly completed
for the United Nations World Summit.

73
00:12:30,416 --> 00:12:36,366
The event promises to be the largest
single gathering of world leaders in history.

74
00:12:37,323 --> 00:12:42,073
Leaders will discuss issues ranging from
the world's economy and weapons treaties,

75
00:12:42,862 --> 00:12:46,781
to the mutant phenomenon
and its impact on our world stage.

76
00:12:47,467 --> 00:12:50,747
American legislators contend
that debate over mutant issues

77
00:12:51,337 --> 00:12:56,087
should be the primary focus of what is,
on the surface at least, a diplomatic affair.

78
00:12:56,876 --> 00:13:00,336
- You owe me some money.
- Stu, let's not do this.

79
00:13:00,947 --> 00:13:04,317
No man takes a beating like that
without a mark to show for it.

80
00:13:04,917 --> 00:13:07,877
- Come on, this isn't worth it.
- [know what you are.

81
00:13:08,454 --> 00:13:12,794
You lost your money.
You keep this up, you lose something else.

82
00:13:14,027 --> 00:13:15,777
Look out!

83
00:13:28,675 --> 00:13:30,604
Get outta my bar, freak.

84
00:15:19,786 --> 00:15:23,565
- What the hell are you doin'?
- I'm sorry. I needed a ride.

85
00:15:24,223 --> 00:15:27,353
- [thought you might help me.
- Get out.

86
00:15:28,661 --> 00:15:30,531
- Where am I supposed to go?
- [don't know.

87
00:15:30,963 --> 00:15:33,772
- You don't know or you don't care?
- Pick one.

88
00:15:37,103 --> 00:15:39,853
- I saved your life.
- No, you didn't.

89
00:15:55,221 --> 00:15:58,151
You don't have anything to eat, do you?

90
00:16:20,079 --> 00:16:21,829
I'm Rogue.

91
00:16:27,487 --> 00:16:30,997
Were you in the army?
Doesn't that mean you were in the army?

92
00:16:39,131 --> 00:16:41,351
- Wow.
- What?

93
00:16:44,270 --> 00:16:46,930
- Suddenly my life isn't bad.
- If you prefer the road...

94
00:16:47,473 --> 00:16:50,433
No. It looks great.

95
00:16:53,980 --> 00:16:56,320
It looks cosy.

96
00:17:03,289 --> 00:17:06,069
Put your hands on the heater.

97
00:17:07,792 --> 00:17:10,453
- I'm not gonna hurt you, kid.
- It's nothing personal.

98
00:17:10,963 --> 00:17:13,923
It's just when people touch my skin,
something happens.

99
00:17:14,500 --> 00:17:16,050
What?

100
00:17:16,469 --> 00:17:18,749
I don't know. They just get hurt.

101
00:17:21,339 --> 00:17:23,419
Fair enough.

102
00:17:26,679 --> 00:17:29,339
When they come out, does it hurt?

103
00:17:32,985 --> 00:17:35,155
Every time.

104
00:17:38,925 --> 00:17:41,175
So what kind of a name is Rogue?

105
00:17:42,695 --> 00:17:45,685
I don't know.
What kind of a name is Wolverine?

106
00:17:51,137 --> 00:17:53,097
My name's Logan.

107
00:17:54,807 --> 00:17:56,767
Marie.

108
00:17:59,145 --> 00:18:02,775
- You should wear your seat belt.
- Look, kid, I don't need advice on...

109
00:19:09,315 --> 00:19:11,595
You all right?

110
00:19:12,051 --> 00:19:14,801
- Kid, are you all right?
- I'm stuck!

111
00:21:00,159 --> 00:21:03,469
Weren't you meant to bring someone back?

112
00:21:16,442 --> 00:21:18,402
- What happened?
- They knew.

113
00:21:27,753 --> 00:21:29,183
Charles...

114
00:21:42,201 --> 00:21:45,451
- Where is the mutant now?
- With them.

115
00:21:48,808 --> 00:21:52,558
I have made the first move.
That is all they know.

116
00:21:54,480 --> 00:21:58,460
Come, the UN summit is approaching.
Time for our little test.

117
00:23:10,923 --> 00:23:13,093
Where's he going?

118
00:23:38,550 --> 00:23:40,889
Where are you going?

119
00:23:48,160 --> 00:23:49,940
Over here.

120
00:24:16,388 --> 00:24:18,638
- Where are you going?
- This way.

121
00:24:19,124 --> 00:24:20,874
He's over there.

122
00:24:27,433 --> 00:24:29,483
Let go! What's your hurry?

123
00:24:34,974 --> 00:24:36,724
Over here.

124
00:24:54,226 --> 00:24:56,416
Good morning, Logan.

125
00:24:56,862 --> 00:25:01,082
So, I'd like your definitions of weak and
strong anthropic principles on Wednesday.

126
00:25:01,834 --> 00:25:03,614
That'll be all.

127
00:25:10,442 --> 00:25:12,402
- Bye, Professor.
- Bye, Kitty.

128
00:25:17,249 --> 00:25:19,029
Physics.

129
00:25:19,752 --> 00:25:22,502
I'm Charles Xavier.
Would you like some breakfast?

130
00:25:23,022 --> 00:25:25,361
- Where am I?
- Westchester, New York.

131
00:25:26,759 --> 00:25:30,159
You were attacked. My people
brought you here for medical attention.

132
00:25:30,829 --> 00:25:34,428
- [don't need medical attention.
- Yes, of course.

133
00:25:36,502 --> 00:25:38,722
- Where's the girl?
- Rogue's here. She's fine.

134
00:25:39,204 --> 00:25:41,104
Really?

135
00:25:42,641 --> 00:25:47,151
Logan, I'd like you to meet Ororo Monroe,
also called Storm.

136
00:25:47,913 --> 00:25:50,603
This is Scott Summers, also called Cyclops.

137
00:25:54,053 --> 00:25:56,163
They saved your life.

138
00:25:57,890 --> 00:26:00,930
I believe you've already met Dr Jean Grey.

139
00:26:01,493 --> 00:26:05,973
You're in my school for the gifted. For
mutants. You'll be safe here from Magneto.

140
00:26:06,732 --> 00:26:09,482
- What's a magneto?
- A very powerful mutant.

141
00:26:10,035 --> 00:26:13,225
Who believes a war is brewing
between mutants and the rest of humanity.

142
00:26:13,872 --> 00:26:16,242
I've been following his activities
for some time.

143
00:26:16,708 --> 00:26:19,838
The man who attacked you
is an associate of his called Sabretooth.

144
00:26:20,446 --> 00:26:21,995
Sabretooth?

145
00:26:23,415 --> 00:26:25,635
Storm.

146
00:26:26,819 --> 00:26:29,399
What do they call you? Wheels?

147
00:26:31,256 --> 00:26:34,416
This is the stupidest thing I've ever heard.

148
00:26:36,128 --> 00:26:38,648
And Cyclops, right?

149
00:26:39,131 --> 00:26:41,271
You wanna get outta my way?

150
00:26:42,734 --> 00:26:45,603
Logan, it's been almost 15 years, hasn't it?

151
00:26:46,738 --> 00:26:49,518
Living from day to day,
moving from place to place

152
00:26:50,075 --> 00:26:52,535
with no memory of who or what you are.

153
00:26:53,045 --> 00:26:55,035
Shut up.

154
00:26:55,481 --> 00:26:59,991
Give me a chance.
I may be able to help you find some answers.

155
00:27:02,087 --> 00:27:04,897
- How do you know?
- You're not the only one with gifts.

156
00:27:05,457 --> 00:27:07,447
- Where are you going?
- Where's he going?

157
00:27:07,926 --> 00:27:09,676
Over here.

158
00:27:14,566 --> 00:27:15,766
What is this place?

159
00:27:18,103 --> 00:27:22,233
Anonymity is a mutant's first defense
against the world's hostility.

160
00:27:22,975 --> 00:27:25,225
No powers!

161
00:27:25,711 --> 00:27:29,521
To the public,
we're merely a school for gifted youngsters.

162
00:27:30,182 --> 00:27:33,582
Cyclops, Storm and Jean
were some of my first students.

163
00:27:34,186 --> 00:27:37,555
I protected them,
taught them to control their powers

164
00:27:38,157 --> 00:27:41,256
and, in time, teach others to do the same.

165
00:27:42,528 --> 00:27:45,808
The students are mostly runaways -
frightened, alone.

166
00:27:46,398 --> 00:27:50,737
Some with gifts so extreme they're a danger
to themselves and those around them.

167
00:27:51,503 --> 00:27:52,963
Like your friend Rogue.

168
00:27:53,338 --> 00:27:57,528
Incapable of physical human contact,
probably for the rest of her life.

169
00:27:58,243 --> 00:28:02,723
And yet here she is with others her own age,
learning, being accepted,

170
00:28:03,515 --> 00:28:05,265
not feared.

171
00:28:16,061 --> 00:28:18,231
- John.
- Sorry.

172
00:28:22,634 --> 00:28:24,654
I'm Bobby.

173
00:28:25,070 --> 00:28:27,060
- What's your name?
- Rogue.

174
00:28:27,472 --> 00:28:29,992
- What'll happen to her?
- That's up to her.

175
00:28:30,475 --> 00:28:34,014
Rejoin the world as an educated
young woman, or stay on to teach others.

176
00:28:34,646 --> 00:28:37,956
To become, what the children
have affectionately called "X-Men."

177
00:28:38,584 --> 00:28:40,664
Welcome to Mutant High.

178
00:28:43,188 --> 00:28:45,798
But the school is merely our public face.

179
00:28:46,291 --> 00:28:50,271
The lower levels, however,
are an entirely different matter.

180
00:28:54,399 --> 00:28:58,438
When I was a boy I discovered I had
the power to control people's minds.

181
00:28:59,171 --> 00:29:01,421
Make them think or do whatever I wanted.

182
00:29:01,873 --> 00:29:05,473
When I was 17
I met a young man named Eric Lensherr.

183
00:29:06,111 --> 00:29:11,151
He, too, had an unusual power. He could
create magnetic fields and control metal.

184
00:29:12,050 --> 00:29:17,290
Believing that humanity would never
accept us, he grew angry and vengeful.

185
00:29:19,591 --> 00:29:21,900
He became Magneto.

186
00:29:23,395 --> 00:29:26,385
There are mutants out there
with incredible powers, Logan.

187
00:29:26,932 --> 00:29:29,952
And many who do not share
my respect for mankind.

188
00:29:30,502 --> 00:29:34,162
If no one is equipped to oppose them,
humanity's days could be over.

189
00:29:34,840 --> 00:29:36,740
I'll make a deal with you.

190
00:29:37,142 --> 00:29:40,712
Give me 48 hours to find out
what Magneto wants with you,

191
00:29:41,346 --> 00:29:43,866
and I give you my word
that I will use all my power

192
00:29:44,349 --> 00:29:48,948
to help you piece together what you've lost,
and what you're looking for.

193
00:30:17,749 --> 00:30:21,789
Senator, you favor gun registration, yes?
Some of these so-called children

194
00:30:22,487 --> 00:30:26,797
possess more than 10 times
the destructive force of any handgun.

195
00:30:27,526 --> 00:30:31,216
No, I don't see a difference.
All I see are weapons in our schools.

196
00:30:31,897 --> 00:30:34,387
Well, that's fair enough. All right.

197
00:30:34,900 --> 00:30:36,480
So?

198
00:30:36,868 --> 00:30:39,998
It's gonna be close.
A vote this loaded is always close.

199
00:30:40,572 --> 00:30:43,322
What about the UN summit?
The world will be watching.

200
00:30:43,875 --> 00:30:47,745
- Maybe you could use it to your advantage.
- We're Americans, Henry.

201
00:30:48,413 --> 00:30:51,603
Let the rest of the damn world
deal with mutants in their own way.

202
00:30:52,184 --> 00:30:54,934
You know this situation? These mutants?

203
00:30:56,588 --> 00:31:01,447
People like this Jean Grey?
If it were up to me, I'd lock 'em all away.

204
00:31:03,695 --> 00:31:05,625
It's a war.

205
00:31:06,031 --> 00:31:08,781
It's the reason people like me exist.

206
00:31:16,541 --> 00:31:18,561
Where the hell are we?

207
00:31:28,787 --> 00:31:30,487
Pilot!

208
00:31:33,525 --> 00:31:37,715
People like you are the reason
I was afraid to go to school as a child.

209
00:32:09,594 --> 00:32:11,344
I'm sorry.

210
00:32:12,697 --> 00:32:15,216
- For what?
- If hurt you.

211
00:32:25,110 --> 00:32:28,540
So... couldn't wait
to get my shirt off again, huh?

212
00:32:45,831 --> 00:32:48,231
The metal is an alloy
called adamantium.

213
00:32:48,700 --> 00:32:53,680
Supposedly indestructible. It's been
surgically grafted to his entire skeleton.

214
00:32:54,506 --> 00:32:57,286
How could he have survived
a procedure like that?

215
00:32:57,843 --> 00:33:04,203
His mutation. He has uncharted regenerative
capability which enables him to heal rapidly.

216
00:33:05,283 --> 00:33:08,243
This also makes his age
impossible to determine.

217
00:33:08,820 --> 00:33:12,129
He could very well be older than you,
Professor.

218
00:33:12,724 --> 00:33:15,214
- Who did this to him?
- He doesn't know.

219
00:33:15,694 --> 00:33:18,654
Nor does he remember anything
about his life before it happened.

220
00:33:19,264 --> 00:33:23,303
Experimentation on mutants.
It's not unheard of.

221
00:33:24,703 --> 00:33:27,312
But I've never seen anything like this before.

222
00:33:27,839 --> 00:33:29,948
What does Magneto want with him?

223
00:33:30,375 --> 00:33:33,595
I'm not entirely sure it's him Magneto wants.

224
00:33:58,470 --> 00:34:01,250
Toad has a wicked tongue, Senator.

225
00:34:01,773 --> 00:34:03,553
Just like you.

226
00:34:10,148 --> 00:34:12,138
Who are you people? Where's Henry?

227
00:34:12,551 --> 00:34:15,831
Mr Guyrich has been dead
for some time, Senator.

228
00:34:16,420 --> 00:34:20,551
But I've had Mystique here keep you
company. She takes so many shapes.

229
00:34:21,326 --> 00:34:24,226
Whatever you do to me, you'll make me right.

230
00:34:24,763 --> 00:34:28,163
Every word I've spoken will be confirmed.

231
00:34:31,570 --> 00:34:36,230
Are you a God-fearing man, Senator?
It's such a strange phrase.

232
00:34:37,007 --> 00:34:39,618
I've always thought of God as a teacher.

233
00:34:40,145 --> 00:34:43,275
As a bringer of light,
wisdom and understanding.

234
00:34:43,848 --> 00:34:47,797
You see,
I think what you really are afraid of is me.

235
00:34:49,454 --> 00:34:52,084
Me and my kind.
The brotherhood of mutants.

236
00:34:55,460 --> 00:35:01,110
It's not so surprising, really. Mankind has
always feared what it doesn't understand.

237
